-content/uploads/Echelon-2013-pitching-startups.png\"><img class=\"alignnone  wp-image-168\" alt=\"Echelon-2013-pitching-startups\" src=\"http://blog.tradehero.mobi/wp-content/uploads/Echelon-2013-pitching-startups.png\" width=\"560\" height=\"412\" /></a></p>\r\n<em>A little information about <strong>Echelon</strong>:</em>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><em>Echelon is a major Asian tech startup conference that gathers the best regional startups held annually. This year, Singapore had the privilege in hosting the event.</em></li>\r\n	<li><em>Over 100 companies around Asia pitched at the 9 satellites that were held, and 10 finalists were shortlisted by their professional team.</em></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<em>For more information, do visit their website at <a href=\"http://e27.co/echelon/\">http://e27.co/echelon/</a></em>','Echelon 2013: Top 10 Promising Startups in Asia','','inherit','closed','open','','154-revision-29','','','2013-06-20 13:21:18','2013-06-20 05:21:18','',154,'http://blog.tradehero.mobi/154-revision-29',0,'revision','',0),(367,4,'2013-07-02 00:31:22','2013-07-01 16:31:22','<a href=\"http://blog.tradehero.mobi/wp-content/uploads/tut3.png\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-268\" alt=\"tut3\" src=\"http://blog.tradehero.mobi/wp-content/uploads/tut3.png\" width=\"750\" height=\"250\" /></a>\r\n\r\nIn this tutorial, we will be showing you a step-by-step process on how to Buy and Sell a stock. Although it may seem simple given that the procedures are easy, it takes more than just steps in the trading world. In order to maximise your experience,we suggest looking beyond this tutorial after you grasp a basic understanding of the application.\r\n<h2><strong>How to Buy/Sell a stock using TradeHero:</strong></h2>\r\nTrade Price is set to the market ask price when buying, and the bid price when selling. This is to simulate Market Order type transactions. For some stocks, we don\'t have ask and bid data. For such stocks, we use the last traded price of the stock. One thing to note: Trade Quantity is limited to 20% of Average Daily Volume or Current Day Volume, whichever is higher.<!--more-->\r\n\r\n1. In the buy/sell screen, select a name of the stock. Use the search engine to search for stocks the supported exchanges. You can search by company or symbol name. Trending stocks simply means the stocks that other TradeHero users are buying and selling.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://blog.tradehero.mobi/wp-content/uploads/buysell.png\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-257\" alt=\"buysell\" src=\"http://blog.tradehero.mobi/wp-content/uploads/buysell.png\" width=\"354\" height=\"551\" /></a>\r\n\r\n2.  Use the charts and information provided on the screen to view market data to help you in your decision on whether to buy or sell a stock. (<em>These information will not be enough, it’s just a guide. You will definitely need more information than that.</em>) Then, use the slider to choose the quantity of stocks that you want to buy. Alternatively, you can use the prefixed amounts found below the slider.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://blog.tradehero.mobi/wp-content/uploads/APPSTORE3_640x1136_2.png\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-258\" alt=\"APPSTORE3_640x1136_2\" src=\"http://blog.tradehero.mobi/wp-content/uploads/APPSTORE3_640x1136_2.png\" width=\"360\" height=\"619\" /></a>\r\n\r\n3. After clicking the Buy button, you can choose to post comments for reasons to buy or sell the stock. You can also choose to share your buy on your social media feeds like Facebook, Twitter and LinkedIn. When you’re done, click on Confirm. And there you go, you have just bought yourself a stock!\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://blog.tradehero.mobi/wp-content/uploads/image-2.png\"><img class=\"alignnone  wp-image-259\" alt=\"image (2)\" src=\"http://blog.tradehero.mobi/wp-content/uploads/image-2-576x1024.png\" width=\"363\" height=\"645\" /></a>\r\n\r\n4.  Similarly, when you want to sell a stock, you can access it through your positions by clicking the middle button and tapping on the <strong>–</strong> button. Then, repeat steps 2 and 3.\r\n\r\nBuying and selling a stock isn\'t all that hard once you get the hang of it. Of course, we strongly advise you to do prior research and read up on the actual stock market before buying or selling a stock. After all, all our data is reflective of the real world and stock market, so why not get more practice to prepare yourself for the real thing?\r\n\r\nAnother important function of the application is the <strong>Trade History</strong>.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://blog.tradehero.mobi/wp-content/uploads/image.png\"><img class=\"alignnone  wp-image-260\" alt=\"image\" src=\"http://blog.tradehero.mobi/wp-content/uploads/image-576x1024.png\" width=\"346\" height=\"614\" /></a>\r\n\r\nThis screen shows the detailed trade history for a position. You can view the quantity bought or sold, the date and the average price paid after the transaction.\r\n\r\n<strong>Realized P&amp;L</strong> is profit or loss banked into your virtual cash after the transaction.\r\n\r\n<strong>Unrealised P&amp;L</strong> is the floating profit or loss due to curret market price of the underlying stocks.\r\n\r\nFind out more at our <a href=\"http://www.tradehero.mobi/FAQ\">FAQ</a> page!\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nOh yes, not forgetting one of the most significant features of TradeHero: <strong>Stock Alerts.</strong>\r\n\r\nStock alerts are designed specially for users to help receive information and keep up to date on stock price movements so that users like you are able to take necessary action at the best possible time. You will receive instant notifications whenever a stock hits a target price or moves by a selected percentage. Such prime information at such a low price, it is definitely a feature not to missed if you want to keep up with the stock market!\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nUsing these information, you will be able to buy and sell a stock on TradeHero easily. Get started! Stay tuned for more tips from TradeHero.  Til then!\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Tutorial Part Two: Buy and Sell','','inherit','closed','open','','256-revision-25','','','2013-07-02 00:31:22','2013-07-01 16:31:22','',256,'http://blog.tradehero.mobi/256-revision-25',0,'revision','',0),(369,4,'2013-07-17 17:33:15','2013-07-17 09:33:15','<a href=\"http://blog.tradehero.mobi/wp-content/uploads/howtochoose.png\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-343\" alt=\"howtochoose\" src=\"http://blog.tradehero.mobi/wp-content/uploads/howtochoose.png\" width=\"750\" height=\"250\" /></a>\n\nMany TradeHero users (especially if you\'re new) may ask, <i>I have the application, but I don\'t know how to choose a stock to invest in? How do I go about researching on stocks if no information is given to me? What do the many financial terms in the application mean? I still don\'t know Market Terminology</i>? Fret not, the answers are right here.\n\nWe will be bringing you through a succinct series on <b>How to choose a Stock</b>. We will also provide you a list of <b>Market Terminology</b> that is essential in your trading journey. (Which is actually found on our <a title=\"FAQ\" href=\"http://www.tradehero.mobi/FAQ\">FAQ</a> page!)\n\n<b>How to Choose A Stock:</b>\n\nBefore you adventure to trade the markets, we suggest you take time to understand the different types of traders out there. When choosing a stock, there are several ways people can choose to analyze, and the two most popular methodologies are <b>Fundamental Analysis</b> and <b>Technical Analysis</b>. This post will be on Fundamental Analysis.\n\nHaving basic knowledge about the stock market will help in investment decisions. Do not worry if you do not understand the many terms and figures that we are about to introduce. Trading takes more than just theoretical assumptions, it requires a fair amount of application as well! Are you ready?\n\n<b>Fundamental Analysis</b>\n\nJust what is fundamental analysis? To put it simply, fundamental analysis is examining the underlying drivers affecting a company’s well being.\n\nTraders often use a <b>Macro -&gt; Micro method</b> (or a top-down approach) when using fundamental analysis, and that comprises of the economy, industry and company analysis. Using a top-down approach will allow you to have better research results according to what you are looking for!\n\nThe three different levels of fundamental analysis:\n<ul>\n	<li>At <b>economy</b> level, fundamental analysts focus on economic indicators and reports to assess how well the economy is doing and how well the economy is going to do in the future. These indicators include GDP, retail sales, inflation and unemployment figures.</li>\n</ul>\n<ul>\n	<li>At <b>industry</b> level, the analysis involves understanding industry supply and demand forces, competition and industry regulation. Often enough, stocks are not lone rangers. They tend to move in groups! Factors such as overall growth rate, market size, and importance to the economy are considered when analyzing industry groups.</li>\n</ul>\n<ul>\n	<li>At <b>company</b> level, fundamental analysis involves the examination of the balance sheet, the income statement, management, the company’s debt and cash flow. Financial and annual reports are usually being used as research material when forecasting profits of the company stocks. This will help in getting a basic understanding of the pricing in the stock market.</li>\n</ul>\n&nbsp;\n\n<b>Fundamental Trading</b>\n\nA good example of fundamental trading and investing is <b>Warren Buffet</b>, who has managed to achieve exceptional returns by analyzing company/industry/economy fundamentals and investing in companies he felt were undervalued.\n\nTrading on fundamentals is associated with a ‘buy and hold’ strategy (long-term) rather than a ‘daily/weekly’ (short term) strategy of investing. There are, however, specific instances in which trading on fundamentals can generate some nice profits in a short period.  This is called momentum trading, which we will revisit in another post!\n\nHere is an example:\n\nLets say you are looking to invest (buy stock) in a company that produces biscuits.  Before you do so, you should ask yourself the following questions:\n\n<span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Company level:</span>\n\nAre the sales increasing year-on-year? Is the product so good/unique that the trend will continue in the following years?\n\nIs the company financially healthy or is it massively in debt?\n\nIs the management preforming a good job; is this reflected in the company’s financial statements?\n\n<span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Industry level:</span>\n\nWho are the competitors? Is there space to grow and achieve market share or is the industry too saturated?\n\nIs there any regulation in the horizon that my affect the company’s profit/sales in the future? (<i>Examples: changes in health and safety, packaging, distribution laws</i>)\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Economy level:</span>\n\n&nbsp;\n\nCan you identify what stage of the economic cycle we are in?\n\nIs there a healthy economic growth in the countries the company operates in? (<i>Controlled inflation, low unemployment, stable consumption</i>)\n\nAre there any upcoming macro economic or political decisions that may dent the company’s sales and operations in those specific countries?\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\nAnother pertinent component is the knowledge of the \'<b>true value\' </b>of a stock.<b> </b>This encompasses the total value of the company.\n\n<i>\"To find the intrinsic value of a company, investors need to determine the market cap – or establish how much it would cost to buy every single share of company stock at current market prices. This is the total value of the company according to the market – including intangibles, fundamentals, and market conditions. A value stock generally has a market cap which is close to or maybe even lower than the book value.\" - InvestorGuide</i>\n\n<i>\"The market price of a stock tends to move towards its \'intrinsic value\', which is the \'true value\' of a company as calculated by its fundamentals. If the market value does not match the true value of the company, there is an investment opportunity.\" - EuroInvestor </i>\n\nThis means that observing the current market price of a stock and comparing it to the \'true value\' of the company will help in decision making as well. If the market price is below the \'true value\', traders and investors will tend to buy the stocks because it will be expected to rise and move towards its \'true value\'.\n\nWhat factors then determine the \'true value\'? Firstly, you must understand that every investor is different in his or her own ways. There is no rigid structure or formula for a sure-win, but these are some of the valuation factors that are often taken:\n\n<b>1. P/E Ratio</b>\n\nThe P/E Ratio is defined as the ratio of the company\'s share price to its earnings per share.\n\n<b><i>P/E Ratio</i></b><i> = Current Share Price /  Earnings per Share</i>\n\nThis ratio helps to determine the amount of expectations investors will put in the company\'s shares in the future. The higher the P/E Ratio, the higher the expectations. Sometimes, the P/E ratio is also known as the \'<a href=\"http://wiki.fool.com/P/e_ratio\">Investor Sentiment</a>\'. It also helps to tell if the company\'s share price is undervalued, overvalued or fairly valued. Usually, the displayed P/E Ratio is the Trailing P/E and it takes the four most recent quarters.\n\nFor instance, if a company attains $0.43, $0.66, $0.31 and $0.24 in EPS and the stock price was $15.63, then the P/E ratio would be $15.63/$1.64 = 9.53.\n\n<b>2. Return on Equity (ROE)</b>\n\nROE is expressed as a percentage, and it helps corporations in calculating their profits by measuring the amount of profit the company earns from the amount the shareholders invest.\n\n<b><i>ROE</i></b><i> = Net Income/ Shareholder\'s Equity</i>\n\nCompanies with higher growth will be expected to have a higher ROE.\n\n<b>3. Profit Margins</b>\n\nProfit Margins define as the \'percentage of revenue that a company keeps as profit after accounting for fixed and variable costs.\' To put it in simpler terms, it can be used to represent profit that the company earns per dollar of revenue. This is usually utilized for internal use among industries as the margins vary across different industries.\n\n<b><i>Profit Margin</i></b><i> = Net Income / Revenue</i>\n\n<b>4. Earnings Per Share (EPS)</b>\n\nEPS represents the portion of the company\'s profit allocated to one share stock.\n\n<b><i>EPS</i></b><i>= Net income / Total number of capital stock shares</i>\n\nThis is important to investors as it provides them a gauge of how their stock share investments are performing in the stock market, and the amount of business earned. Especially for traders dealing with public trading,  they want information such as the net income provided on a per share basis so that they can easily compare it with the market price of their stock shares.\n\n<i> </i>\n\nFor more information and to find out the strengths and weaknesses of Fundamental Analysis, we recommend that you visit the following websites:\n\n<i><a href=\"http://stockcharts.com/school/doku.php?id=chart_school:overview:fundamental_analysis\">Stock Charts</a></i>\n\n<i><a href=\"http://www.euroinvestor.com/ei-news/2012/02/12/stock-school-5-important-elements-in-fundamental-analysis/15694\">Euro Investor </a></i>\n\n<i> </i>\n\nAs you can see, the more detailed is your analysis, the more you will know about the company/stock and the more confident you will be with your final decision. You will certainly need to put in an effort to become our top Hero!\n\n&nbsp;\n\nRemember that when you select a stock on TradeHero, you can read stock related news on the Buy/Sell screens. So before you make a decision, take in as much updated information as you can!\n\nStay tuned for the next post on <b>Technical Analysis</b>!\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<address><strong>Resources:</strong></address><address>http://accountingexplained.com/financial/ratios/pe-ratio</address><address>http://wiki.fool.com/P/e_ratio</address><address>http://www.investorguide.com/article/12293/stock-strategies-basics-of-the-value-investing-stock-strategy-igu/</address><address>http://www.investopedia.com/terms/r/returnonequity.asp</address><address>http://ycharts.com/glossary/terms/profit_margin</address><address><address>http://stockcharts.com/school/doku.php?id=chart_school:overview:fundamental_analysis</address><address>http://www.euroinvestor.com/ei-news/2012/02/12/stock-school-5-important-elements-in-fundamental-analysis/15694</address></address>','How to Choose A Stock: Fundamental Analysis','','inherit','closed','open','','295-revision-19','','','2013-07-17 17:33:15','2013-07-17 09:33:15','',295,'http://blog.tradehero.mobi/295-revision-19',0,'revision','',0),(370,4,'2013-07-17 17:34:15','2013-07-17 09:34:15','<a href=\"http://blog.tradehero.mobi/wp-content/uploads/howtochoose.png\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-343\" alt=\"howtochoose\" src=\"http://blog.tradehero.mobi/wp-content/uploads/howtochoose.png\" width=\"750\" height=\"250\" /></a>\n\nMany TradeHero users (especially if you\'re new) may ask, <i>I have the application, but I don\'t know how to choose a stock to invest in? How do I go about researching on stocks if no information is given to me? What do the many financial terms in the application mean? I still don\'t know Market Terminology</i>? Fret not, the answers are right here.\n\nWe will be bringing you through a succinct series on <b>How to choose a Stock</b>. We will also provide you a list of <b>Market Terminology</b> that is essential in your trading journey. (Which is actually found on our <a title=\"FAQ\" href=\"http://www.tradehero.mobi/FAQ\">FAQ</a> page!)\n\n<b>How to Choose A Stock:</b>\n\nBefore you adventure to trade the markets, we suggest 