arrants was the first runner-up Rinson. Rinson, a 25 year-old who works in the uniformed services,is relatively new to investing in equity markets. WarrantHero gave him his first introduction to warrants, which he had no knowledge of prior to the game. Now, he likes the instrument for the fact that “it can go up a lot and make you a lot of money when your view is right.”\r\n\r\nWith a bearish view over local property developer, CapitaLand, Rinson chose the short dated put warrant CapitalaMBePW130903 (R5TW). He entered the position on 16 Aug, when CapitaLand gapped down to open at $3.19. Rinson has yet to close off his position on the put warrants, giving him an unrealised profit of 55% as of Friday’s close. The underlying security, Capitaland slid 4.7% over the corresponding period.\r\n\r\nBesides trading CapitaLand puts on 16 Aug, Rinson also made two other trades on Keppel Corporation put warrant KepCorp MBePW131101 (SH9W). This position gave Rinson a return of more than 6.6% after the company lost 1.8% in the next two weeks.\r\n\r\nWith an overall return on investment of more than 46%, Rinson is the first runner up for the WarrantHero contest in August, a decent set of results for someone who is just starting to pick up trading in the real world.\r\n\r\n<strong>Second runner-up an index trader who trades a mix of HSI and Nikkei</strong>\r\n\r\nThe second runner-up Aaron, is a 26-year old Management Associate at an offshore and marine company who ranked top 10 in a previous Macquarie warrant competition and has managed to repeat his feat in this contest.\r\n\r\nHe closely monitors index futures in the real world and is a HSI warrant investor. His winning trades in the contest were invariably HSI put warrants, where he managed to profit from the fall in the HSI futures. He entered his HSI22000 MBePW130927 (SO9W) position on 13 Aug<del cite=\"mailto:hng\" datetime=\"03 Sep 2013T18:03\">,</del>before the HSI futures declined. He held the position over a period of over 2 weeks, realizing his profits last Wednesday. The put warrants gave Aaron a total return of 46% over his 2 week holding period.\r\n\r\nAfter closing out the winning trade in the HSI puts, Aaron bought into a longer dated HSI put, however the market did not move in his favour and he was quick to square his position. Similarly he took a bullish position on the Japanese market, buying Nikkei call warrant NKY 11000 MBeCW130913 (S9SW). The Nikkei 225 futures climbed steadily after Aaron entered the position, before it retraced shortly after. Aaron then closed off his position at his same entry price. A good lesson here for budding traders, always have stop losses be quick to close out trades if your initial view turns out to be wrong!\r\n\r\n<strong>Weekly winners bought puts on HSI, UOB and DBS</strong>\r\n\r\nNot just a monthly winner, Aaron was also the weekly winner last week, earning a weekly return of more than 28% on his position over as the futures declined approximately 391 points, or 1.8% over the week. Runner up Aikobanana also bought into HSI puts, buying HSI21400 MBePW130927 (SO8W) last Monday before the Hang Seng futures started their decline. Aikobanana held an unrealised profit of 23.4% based on the closing price on last Friday, 30 Aug. Aikobanana has yet to close off his position in the puts.\r\n\r\nTrader SuperBear, just as the name suggests, had a bearish view over the banking stocks in Singapore. He bought into the put warrants over two local banks in Singapore last Monday. SuperBear chose to buy DBS put warrant DBS MBePW131101 (SG3W), as well as UOB put warrant UOB MBePW131105 (SI6W). SuperBear profited approximately 30% from both DBS and UOB put warrants as the underlying DBS and UOB bank lost about 3.1% and 3.8% respectively. Superbear has yet to close out his positions.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>','August Winners Trade Analysis','','inherit','closed','open','','486-revision-2','','','2013-09-05 13:17:56','2013-09-05 05: